`render()` (`app.js:111-143`) does `refs.todoList.innerHTML = ""` and rebuilds **every** `.todo-item` node from scratch on **every** mutation — adding one task, toggling one checkbox, or switching a filter all wipe and recreate the entire list, including 3 fresh event listeners per item (`createTodoItem`, `app.js:145-179`).

```js
// app.js:128-142 — current: O(n) teardown/rebuild for any single change
refs.todoList.innerHTML = "";
...
todos.forEach((todo) => fragment.appendChild(createTodoItem(todo)));
```

Fix with event delegation so listeners are attached once, not per item per render:

```js
// attach once, outside render()
refs.todoList.addEventListener("click", (event) => {
  const item = event.target.closest(".todo-item");
  if (!item) return;
  const { id } = item.dataset;
  if (event.target.closest(".check-btn")) toggleTodo(id);
  if (event.target.closest(".del-btn")) deleteTodo(id);
});

// in createTodoItem: drop the two addEventListener calls on checkBtn/deleteBtn,
// just set: item.dataset.id = todo.id;
```

This doesn't eliminate the DOM rebuild itself (fine at to-do-list scale, dozens of items), but it removes the repeated listener allocation/teardown, which is the real cost driver as the list grows.

`render()` walks `state.todos` 3-4 times per call:

```js
// app.js:48-54, 111-114
function getActiveCount() { return state.todos.filter(...).length; }       // pass 1
function getCompletedCount() { return state.todos.length - getActiveCount(); } // pass 2 (calls pass 1 again)
// render() also calls filteredTodos() separately                          // pass 3
```

Collapse into one pass:

```js
function getCounts() {
  return state.todos.reduce(
    (acc, t) => (t.completed ? acc.completed++ : acc.active++, acc),
    { active: 0, completed: 0 }
  );
}
```
Use the result for both `activeText` and `markAllBtn`/`clearCompletedBtn` state instead of calling `getActiveCount`/`getCompletedCount` separately.

